04561nam a22006375i 9780804778497DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202012cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047784977 a10.1515/97808047784972doi  a(DE-B1597)563654  a(OCoLC)1178769953  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDR1629b.R45 2012eb 7aHIS0100102bisacsh04a320.540945/3090342221 aReill, Dominique Kirchner, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNationalists Who Feared the Nation :bAdriatic Multi-Nationalism in Habsburg Dalmatia, Trieste, and Venice /cDominique Kirchner Reill. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies on Central and Eastern Europe00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tNames and Languages -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Adriatic and the Romance of National Variety -- t2 Niccolò Tommaseo: Progress Through Multi-Nationalism -- t3 Trieste: The Center of a Multi-National Adriatic -- t4 Multi-Nationalism in Dalmatia: From a Means to an End -- t5 1848: A Rupture in Experience -- t6 1848: A Crisis for Multi-Nationalism? -- tConclusion : From Bridge to Border- The Adriatic in the Nineteenth Century -- tAbbreviations for Archive Materials -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe can often learn as much from political movements that failed as from those that achieved their goals. Nationalists Who Feared the Nation looks at one such frustrated movement: a group of community leaders and writers in Venice, Trieste, and Dalmatia during the 1830s, 40s, and 50s who proposed the creation of a multinational zone surrounding the Adriatic Sea. At the time, the lands of the Adriatic formed a maritime community whose people spoke different languages and practiced different faiths but identified themselves as belonging to a single region of the Hapsburg Empire. While these activists hoped that nationhood could be used to strengthen cultural bonds, they also feared nationalism's homogenizing effects and its potential for violence. This book demonstrates that not all nationalisms attempted to create homogeneous, single-language, -religion, or -ethnicity nations. Moreover, in treating the Adriatic lands as one unit, this book serves as a correction to "national" histories that impose our modern view of nationhood on what was a multinational region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCultural pluralismxHistoryx19th centuryxCroatiaxDalmatia. 0aCultural pluralismxHistoryx19th centuryxItalyxTrieste. 0aCultural pluralismxHistoryx19th centuryxItalyxVenice. 0aCultural pluralismzCroatiazDalmatiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aCultural pluralismzItalyzTriestexHistoryy19th century. 0aCultural pluralismzItalyzVenicexHistoryy19th century. 0aNationalismxHistoryx19th centuryxCroatiaxDalmatia. 0aNationalismxHistoryx19th centuryxItalyxTrieste. 0aNationalismxHistoryx19th centuryxItalyxVenice. 0aNationalismzCroatiazDalmatiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aNationalismzItalyzTriestexHistoryy19th century. 0aNationalismzItalyzVenicexHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804778497zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804778497423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804778497.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles